1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nc3 { The most active way of development. In comparison to 5...Nbd2 White leaves his bishop unblocked and takes control over d5 and e4 squares. On the downside, it makes it tougher for White to regain the pawn after ...dxc4. } 5... O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 { Capturing the pawn is the most ambitious and logical reaction. } 7. a3 { White spends a tempo in order to exchange opponent's bishop. } ( { Dubious is } 7. Ne5 $6 { This position is very similar to Catalan with 4...Be7, but the difference clearly favors Black. } 7... Nd5 { This is the point. Black takes advantage of pin to cover the c4-pawn. } 8. Bd2 ( { Worse is } 8. Qc2 $6 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Qxd4 10. Bb2 Ba5 $17 ) 8... Nb6 $1 { Black covers c4 with a tempo - d4 is hanging. } 9. e3 ( { Also after } 9. a3 Be7 10. Bf4 f6 11. Nf3 Nc6 { White has no real compensation for the pawn. } ) 9... f6 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. O-O e5 { Black was clearly better in Bastian,H - Neunhoeffer,H Germany 1987 } ) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 c5 { The most energetic response - Black is trying to make a use of extra tempo to undermine opponent's pawn centre. } 9. O-O { The most common by far. White ins't in a rush with regaining the pawn as he build } ( { The other options are: } 9. Qa4 cxd4 10. cxd4 { took place in Dziuba,M - Roiz,M Lublin 2009 Here Black can choose between few decent possibilities, but the most ambitious is } 10... Qd5 $14 11. Qc2 Bd7 { Activating the bishop and taking more control of e4. } 12. O-O Bc6 13. Re1 Nbd7 14. e4 Qa5 $1 { This move is safer than 14...Nxe4, although Black can do with opposition along the h1-a8 diagonal. } 15. Bb2 Qa4 $15 { White doesn't have real compensation for the pawn. } ) ( 9. Ne5 Nd5 10. dxc5 { , as in Conover,W - Rohde,M Somerset 1986 can be well met by } 10... Qa5 $14 11. Qd4 Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 { White's bishop pair is fully compensated by Black's active piece play: } 13. O-O ( { Equally possible is } 13. Bd2 Re8 14. O-O e5 15. Qxc4 Ba6 16. Qe4 Qxc5 $11 ) 13... Nxc3 { Black gains an important tempo due to attack on e2. } 14. Bf3 Rd8 15. Qxc4 Ba6 { All Black's pieces are rather active now. } 16. Qg4 Qxc5 17. Be3 Qc4 $11 { Black liquidates into a comfortable endgame. } ) 9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 { This was played in most of high-level games. } ( { After } 10. cxd4 { Black easily solves his issues with development by means of } 10... Bd7 $1 11. Bg5 Bc6 12. Qc2 Nbd7 $14 { A simple approach - White is allowed to grab the pawn, but it will cost him few tempi. } ( { Instead, the ''materialistic'' } 12... b5 13. a4 a6 { Halkias, S - Svane,R Chess.com INT 2022 runs into } 14. Bxf6 $14 Qxf6 15. Rfb1 { , and then White has interesting play for the pawn. For instance, } 15... Nd7 $2 { is bad in view of } 16. Ng5 Qxg5 17. Bxc6 $16 ) 13. Qxc4 h6 14. Bf4 Rc8 { Black has excellent prospects on the queenside. White's bishop pair doesn't seem to play an important role here. } ) 10... Nc6 11. Qxc4 { White regains the pawn, but his queen is still vulnerable and the c3-pawn is weak. } 11... e5 { Black grabs some space and activates his bishop. } 12. Bg5 h6 13. Rfd1 Be6 $1 { A little finese. There is no need to waste a tempo for moving the queen. } 14. Qc5 ( { After } 14. Rxd8 Bxc4 15. Rxa8 Rxa8 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Kf1 Na5 { vulnerablity of White's queenside pawns overweights some structural drawbacks on the kingside. } ) 14... Qa5 15. Be3 $14 { White has to maintain his both bishops. } ( { Worse is } 15. Qxa5 Nxa5 16. Bxf6 gxf6 $15 { Black was clearly better in Bykov,E - Ter Sahakyan,S Chess.com INT 2022 } ) 15... Qxc5 16. Bxc5 Rfd8 { White has to play accurately in order to equalize because Black's } *
