1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. O-O Nc6 8. Re1 { This move shows White's clear intention to extend in the centre with e2-e4. It has gained popularity in the last few years. } ( 8. Qc2 { is played with similar ideas, but it lives d4 unprotected. } 8... Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Rd1 { White gains some tempi by attacking the queen, but it isn't enough. } 10... Qb6 11. Na4 Qa6 12. Rd4 { This position took place in Miladinovic,I - Andrejic,V Kragujevac 2015 Now Black could have consolidate and keep the extra pawn by means of } 12... c6 13. Rxc4 Be7 $15 ) ( 8. e3 { makes some sense because the d4-pawn is covered, so White can move his f3-knight. Still, it is too passive and not in spirit of White's previous gambit play. } 8... Rb8 { Black avoids opposition on the long diagonal and prepares .. .b7-b5. } 9. Qc2 ( { In case of } 9. Qe2 b5 10. Rd1 { Black can effectively neutralize White's play along the long diagonal by means of } 10... Nd5 $1 11. Bd2 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nb6 13. e4 Na4 14. Rac1 Ne7 $15 { White has no adequate compensation for the pawn in Valeinis,J - Plomp,M ICCF email 2014 } ) ( { Worse is } 9. Nd2 $6 e5 $1 10. d5 Na5 11. Qa4 { This was Siegel,G - Wirthensohn, H Germany 2003 Among Black's decent options, I find most convincing: } 11... Qe7 $14 12. a3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 b6 14. e4 Qd7 $17 { Black is up a pawn in good position. } ) 9... b5 10. Rd1 Qe8 $1 { Avoiding dangerous opposiiton with d1-rook and covering the knight. } 11. e4 e5 12. dxe5 { This position occured in Bezold, M - Romanishin,O Balatonbereny 1995 Black should have continued: } 12... Ng4 $1 13. Nd5 Bc5 14. Rf1 { A sad necessity. This passive move is the only way to cover f2. } 14... Ngxe5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxc7 { Whtie regains the pawn, but it costs him wasting few tempi. } 16... Qc6 17. Nd5 Be6 $15 { Black is much better rmobilized. } ) ( 8. Rb1 { This somewhat artificial move was played by few strong players. White chooses a moment for ..a2-a3 to make a use of b1-rook. } 8... a6 9. a3 Be7 10. Qa4 { White is aiming to involve his rooks, but it costs him losing a central pawn. } ( { After } 10. Ne5 Nxe5 ( 10... Nxd4 $5 11. Nxc4 Nb5 { also seems to offer Black solid position with extra pawn. } ) 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. f4 Rb8 { White's compensation for the pawn is questionable. Carter,M - Abbey,W ICCF email 2015 } ) 10... Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Be3 { This was Ris,R - Bok,B Riga 2014 My natural new idea is } 12... Qg4 $14 13. h3 Qh5 14. Qxc4 ( { Worse is } 14. g4 Qe5 15. Qxc4 Bd6 $17 { White's king turns very unsafe. } ) 14... Bd6 { Defending the c7-pawn and intending to push e6-e5. } 15. f4 Nd5 $1 { Vulnerablity of h3-pawn makes it possible for Black to play this move. } 16. Bd4 b5 17. Qc6 Rb8 $15 { Activity of Whute's pieces is neutralized. } ) 8... a6 { Black is ready to connect his queenside pawns with ... b7-b5 to defend his pawn. } ( 8... Rb8 $5 { also scores well for Black, and it is actually more common. } ) 9. e4 ( 9. a3 Ba5 10. e4 h6 { is another possible moves order. } ) ( { Dubious is } 9. Bg5 $6 h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 Be7 { White has no real attack, and piece is a piece. } ) 9... h6 { Black can afford spending a tempo for prophylacsis. } 10. a3 ( { An alternative aggressive try is } 10. e5 Nd5 11. Bd2 b5 12. Re4 ( { Hardly better is } 12. Qc1 { White declares his intend to capture h6 in order to make some threats against g8-king. } 12... f5 13. exf6 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qxf6 $15 { White's attack is neutralized. } ) 12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nce7 $1 14. Qc1 Nf5 { Black manages to secure his king. For instance, } 15. g4 Nfe7 16. Bxh6 Nxc3 $1 { Deflection. White cannot afford moving his queen from c1-h6 diagonal. } 17. Re1 Ncd5 18. Bg5 Rb8 { In this unbalanced position Black's positional merits (control of d5 and strong passers) prevail. } ) 10... Ba5 11. e5 { White grabs space and blocks the c8-bishop. On the hand, it traditionally concesses control of d5. } ( { In the event of } 11. a4 Rb8 12. Qe2 b5 13. axb5 axb5 { White also doesn't achieve much for the pawn. } ) 11... Nd5 12. Qc2 b5 13. Re4 $14 { The rooks is hanging on g4 or h4. This novelty is very much in spirit of White's previous play. } ( { Inconsistent is } 13. Rd1 $6 Rb8 14. Ne2 Nce7 $17 { Black was just up a pawn in Stagl,M - Schnegg,D Deutschlandsberg 2006 } ) 13... f5 $1 { Black neutralizes activity of opponent's rook. } 14. exf6 Qxf6 15. Bd2 Bd7 16. Rae1 Rae8 $15 { White has no sufficient compensation. } *
