1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3 { This is White's top choice. Black should either concess his bishop and strengten White's centre or retreat it, and then it makes e2-e4 possible. } 8... Be7 { I find this move more challenging for White than 8...Bxc3. } 9. e4 ( { In the event of } 9. Qa4 Nxd4 10. Rd1 Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Qe8 12. Qxc4 c6 $15 { Black has a solid position, and the extra pawn counts. } ) 9... a6 { As in most of cases, Black is interested in connecting his pawn chain with b7-b5. White has to play very energetically to claim any compensation for the pawn. } 10. Be3 ( { The other setup with } 10. Bf4 { is less promising for White: } 10... b5 11. Qe2 ( { Insufficient is } 11. d5 exd5 12. e5 ( 12. exd5 Na5 13. Qc2 Bd6 $17 { was bad for White in Klaasen,C - Vazquez,G Batumi 2018 } ) 12... Ne4 13. Nxd5 Nc5 $15 { Black's knight reaches d3. White doesn't have adequate compensation for the pawn. } ) ( 11. Qc2 $6 { was seen in on GM's level either, but it meets } 11... Nxd4 $14 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. e5 ( 13. Rad1 Qa7 14. e5 Nd5 { leads to the same. } ) 13... Nd5 14. Rad1 Qa7 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Bxd5 Rb8 $17 { , and White has nothing for the pawn. } ) 11... Bb7 12. Rad1 Na5 13. d5 { The most straightforward attempt to extend initiative in the centre. } ( { The other options are: } 13. Ne5 Nb3 14. d5 exd5 15. exd5 Bd6 16. Nc6 Qd7 $15 { White's activity was neutralized in Flom,G - Beliavsky,A Skopje 2019 } ) ( { and } 13. h4 Nb3 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bf4 { This was Halkias,S - Lenderman,A St Petersburg 2012 Black should have played } 15... c5 $14 16. dxc5 Qe8 $17 { White's attacking plans are interrupted, Black is just a pawn up. } ) 13... exd5 14. e5 Nh5 $1 { The h5-knight is in danger, but Black needs to gain a tempo. } 15. Be3 g6 16. e6 { Natural play by both sides led to this position in Refalo,J - Maetzig,R ICCF email 2011 In my opinion, Black should have consolidated by means of } 16... f6 $14 17. Nd4 Ng7 { The position is closed, and White struggles to extend his initiative. A likely continuation is: } 18. Bh6 c5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Nf5+ { A desperate try. White has to go all in! } 20... gxf5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 Qe8 $17 { Black's material advantage prevails. } ) ( 10. Qe2 b5 11. Rd1 { is practically unexplored. In my opinion, Black has few reasonable ways to meet d4-d5, including } 11... Na5 12. d5 exd5 13. e5 c6 $1 { Black strenghtens d5 and neutralizes dangerous opposition on the d-file. } 14. exf6 Bxf6 $15 { The mobile passers oveweights White's extra piece. } ) 10... b5 11. h4 { This move creates 2 ideas: further extension with h4-h5-h6 and vacating g5 for the f3-knight. } ( { The quieter possibilities are: } 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Rad1 Na5 13. Ne5 ( { Or } 13. d5 exd5 14. e5 Ne8 $17 ) 13... Qe8 $1 { Black moves his queen away from opposition along the d-file. } 14. f4 Rd8 15. g4 { We were following White's aggressive play in the game Sambuev,B - Roussel Roozmon,T Contrecoeur 2019 Here I suggest } 15... Nb3 $14 16. g5 Nd7 17. h4 c5 $1 { Black reacts energetically to undermine opponent's strong pawn centre before the attack begins. } 18. d5 Nd4 19. Qf2 f5 $17 { The strong d4-knight makes it possible for Black to start his counter-attack and maintain the extra pawn. } ) ( { and } 11. Qc2 Ng4 12. Bf4 g5 $1 { A decent move. Black weakens his king, but forces an exchange of opponent's important bishop. } ( { In case of } 12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. e5 { White has promising compensation for 2 pawns. } ) 13. Be3 Nxe3 14. fxe3 g4 15. Nh4 { This position occured in Theodorou,N - Samaridis,K Paleochora 2019 Now I suggest the following new concept: } 15... e5 $14 { Locking the g2-bishop and fixing th centre. } 16. Nf5 Kh8 17. Rad1 Bd6 $1 { Blocking the d-file and clearing the diagonal for d8-queen. } 18. Qf2 Qg5 $13 { Black's chances are by no means worse. } ) 11... Rb8 12. e5 { We have been following the game Theodorou, N - Hakobyan,A Saint Louis 2022 In my opinion, the most natural continuation would be } 12... Nd5 $14 13. Ng5 b4 { Black has time for developing his counterplay on the opposite side. } 14. Qc2 ( { After } 14. axb4 $6 Ncxb4 15. Qh5 h6 16. Nge4 Qe8 17. Qg4 Kh8 $15 { Black manages to parry all the threats. White is on the verge of collapse. } ) 14... Bxg5 15. Bxg5 Nxd4 $1 { An important intermediate move. } 16. Qd1 f6 17. Qxd4 fxg5 18. Nxd5 Bb7 $1 { The pin allows Black to grab the knight in favorable redaction. Equality is out of questions. } *
