1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. O-O Nc6 8. Bg5 { One of White's most common options. He concesses the dark-squared bishop, but vacates c1 for his rook and diminshes Blacks control of e4. } 8... h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. e3 { The most common and consistent move. After getting a rid of dark-squared bishop White feels free to strenghten d4. } ( { Harmless is } 10. Rc1 { with a clear intention to play Nc3-e4 and grab the pawn } 10... Rb8 11. Ne4 Qf5 { Once again, this seems the most attractive square for a retreat. } 12. Ned2 b5 13. Nh4 { A double attack, but Black can do with it. } 13... Qg5 14. Nxc4 { White regains the pawn, but it isn't a big achievement. } 14... bxc4 15. Bxc6 Ba6 { Black has bishop pait and decent play along the b-file. Prusikin,M - Kritz,L Griesheim 2003 } ) ( { Or } 10. Ne4 Qf5 11. Ned2 ( { Worse is } 11. Qc2 $2 Be7 12. Rac1 b5 $17 { White's compensation for the pawn doesn't exist. Bletz,H - Eng,H Germany 1986 } ) 11... Bxd2 12. Qxd2 e5 { Black activates his c8-bishop, so only White may face any difficulties. Baranowski,T - Risquet,C ICCF email 2017 } ) 10... Rb8 { Black is ready to connect his queenside pawns with ...b7-b5. } 11. Ne4 ( { For some reason, the top choice by statistics is } 11. Nd2 Na5 12. Qc2 ( { After } 12. Qh5 $6 Qg5 13. Qxg5 hxg5 $17 { White was on the verge of collapse in Gurevich,D - Ellers,H Ischia 1997 } ) 12... Qd8 { The queen did its job on f6, so now Black moves it back. } 13. a3 Be7 14. Ne2 b5 15. a4 c6 $15 { Black manages to maintain both the extra pawn and bishop pair. Sulava,N - Lukacs,P Budapest 1990 } ) 11... Qf5 { The queen isn't in dnager because it has few several squares for a retreat. } 12. a3 $14 { This move is more accurate } ( { than } 12. Nfd2 b5 13. a4 a6 14. b3 Na5 15. axb5 axb5 16. bxc4 bxc4 $15 { White had no much for the pawn in Potapov,A - Yakovich, Y Salekhard 2007 } ) 12... Be7 13. Nfd2 b5 14. a4 { White is naturally interested in seperating opponent's pawns or getting control over a-file. } 14... a6 15. axb5 axb5 16. b3 e5 $5 { I like this dynamic approach. Black opens the game in favor of bishop pair. } ( { After } 16... cxb3 17. Qxb3 Bb7 18. Rfc1 { White has full compensation for the pawn due to pressure along the c-file. } ) 17. d5 Nb4 18. bxc4 Rd8 $11 { Black has fully mobilized his forces. Most likely, all the queenside pawns will be liquidated soon. } *
