1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nbd2 { An ambitious and somewhat risky choice. White blocks his dark-quared bishop and leaves c4-pawn hanging. On the other hand, the b4-bishop isn't placed well, and White is ready to take the upper hand in the centre with e2-e4. } 5... dxc4 6. a3 { A challenging move - the c4-pawn isn't covered yet, so Black s forced to concess his bishop. } ( 6. Qc2 b5 7. a4 c6 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O O-O { This important position might be reached also with 6.Bg2 b5, when White plays Qd1-c2 in the later stage. } 10. b3 ( { After } 10. Rd1 a5 11. b3 c3 12. Nb1 bxa4 $1 { Black manages to activate his fnachettoes bishop and solve all the problems. For instance, } 13. bxa4 ( 13. Rxa4 c5 14. Nxc3 Nbd7 $15 ) 13... c5 14. Nxc3 ( 14. dxc5 Qe7 15. Nxc3 Na6 $11 ) 14... cxd4 15. Nb5 Be4 16. Qb2 Nc6 $11 { The d4-pawn will fall soon, but Black has nothing to worry about. Stany,G - Ramoutar,A Seville 2023 } ) ( { Another risky approach is } 10. e4 Nbd7 11. e5 Nd5 12. Ne4 { White builds only on threats against opponent's king. } 12... h6 $1 13. Bd2 a5 $15 { Black's pawn majority on the queenside overwhelms White's attacking prospects. Carlsen,M - Ivanisevic,I Heraklion 2007 } ) 10... c5 { One of few decent ways - Black solves the issues with b7-bishop at once. } 11. bxc4 bxc4 12. Nxc4 cxd4 13. Qb3 Nc6 { Black had a comfortable play in Perico,A - Morau,J IECG email 2007 } ) ( 6. Qa4+ $6 { is a dubious idea. Even though the c6-knight isn't placed optimally, White wastes a crucial tempo and places his queen awkwardly. } 6... Nc6 7. a3 ( { Hardly more attractive is } 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Rb8 9. Ne5 { White is trying to claim vulnerablity of b4-bishop, but it meets } 9... b5 $1 10. Nxc6 bxa4 11. Nxd8 Rxd8 12. Nxc4 Ba6 $17 { The edngame was difficult for White because all Black's pieces are very active. Koykka,P - Rathanvel,V Stockholm 2020 } ) 7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Qd5 { Black covers c4 and makes b7-b5 possible. } 9. Bc3 b5 10. Qc2 Bb7 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O a5 { Black has the superior chances, when the careless } 13. Ne5 $2 Qxg2+ 14. Kxg2 Nxd4+ { loses on a spot. } ) 6... Bxd2+ 7. Bxd2 a6 { For some reason, this move is relatively rare. At the same time, Black makes last preparations for ...b7-b5. } ( { In case of } 7... b5 8. a4 c6 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. b3 $44 { The bishop pair provides White decent compensation for the pawn. } ) 8. Bg2 ( { Equal alternative is } 8. a4 b6 9. Rc1 ( { After } 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Qxc4 { White grabs the pawn, but loses few tempi. } 10... Bd5 11. Qd3 Be4 12. Qa3 Nc6 $15 { The lack of development makes it tough for White do cover d4. Korley,K - Gretarsson,H Reykjavik 2016 } ) 9... b5 { This move is possible because White's rook left the a-file. } 10. axb5 ( { After } 10. b3 cxb3 11. Qxb3 Bb7 12. axb5 Bd5 13. Qd3 O-O { Black had an excellent play in Kolanek,R - Goreczny G LSS email 2017 } ) 10... axb5 11. b3 Bb7 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. Bg2 ( { In case of } 13. Rxc4 Bd5 14. Rc1 Nc6 { White faces problems with defending d4. } ) 13... Bd5 { This is a perfect spot for Black's light squared bishop. } 14. Bg5 Nbd7 15. O-O Ra2 $11 { The c4-pawn will most likely fall, but it isn't a bid deal - Black has no problems. Datta,D - Mytsko,V ICCF email 2018 } ) 8... b5 9. Ne5 $14 { This most natural move is a novelty. } ( { Worse is } 9. O-O Bb7 10. b3 cxb3 11. Qxb3 O-O 12. Rac1 Bd5 { White struggles to claim sufficient compensation for the pawn because d5-bishop is a monster. Rekhtman,P - Kochan, I ICCF email 2016 } ) 9... Ra7 10. O-O ( 10. Bb4 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Rxb7 12. O-O { leads to the same. } ) 10... Bb7 11. Bxb7 Rxb7 12. Bb4 Qd5 $1 { Black can do with a fact that his king is stuck in the centre. For instance, } 13. f3 ( { Worse is } 13. a4 a5 14. Be1 c6 15. axb5 cxb5 16. Bxa5 O-O $15 ) 13... Nc6 14. Nxc6 Qxc6 15. e4 { making a strong pawn centre is White's undenieble achievement. } 15... a5 $1 16. Bxa5 O-O 17. Qd2 Nd7 { Black has decent counter-attacking prospects with ... c7-c5 or e6-e5. } *
