1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nbd2 dxc4 6. Bg2 b5 7. O-O O-O 8. a4 { This move is the most challenging for Black - 8...c6 is practically forced, and then the long diagonal becomes more exposed. } 8... c6 { Now White is at crossroads. There are few attempt of extending initiative. } 9. Ne1 { A top choice White unblocks his strong g2-bishop, while his knight moves towards c2 in order to chase the active b4-bishop. } ( { The other possibilities are: } 9. axb5 cxb5 10. Ng5 { The most aggressive retreat. White keeps an eye on h7. } ( 10. Nh4 { was tested in some corr games, but hardly it is equally good } 10... Nd5 11. e4 Nc7 12. e5 a5 $14 { I like this calm response - Black siglans that his queenside passers is the crucial factor. } ( { Instead, the ''greedy'' } 12... Qxd4 $6 13. Qh5 g6 14. Qg5 { put Black's king in big danger in Umansky,M - Rause,O ICCF corr 2003 } ) 13. Ne4 ( { In the event of } 13. Bxa8 Nxa8 14. Qf3 Qd5 $17 { Black's pawn majority on the queenside offers Black a huge advantage. } ) 13... Ra6 14. Qh5 { White goes all in! } 14... Nd5 15. Ng5 ( { After } 15. Bg5 Be7 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 { White doesn't have sufficient attacking potential. } ) 15... h6 16. Ne4 { The h6-pawn is a target, but White wasted 2 tempi. } 16... f5 17. exf6 Qe8 $15 { White cannot afford trading queens, but otherwise his attack is neutralized. } ) 10... Nd5 { The only, but sufficient defense. } 11. e4 Nc7 ( 11... Qxg5 12. exd5 exd5 13. Nxc4 $44 ) 12. Nxh7 $1 { This is the only way to justify White's ambitious play - his chances are connected only with a direct attack on Black's king. } 12... Kxh7 13. e5 { Of course, White is aiming to obtain a strong tandem of Qh5+Ng5. } 13... g6 { Preventing . .Qh5 } 14. Bxa8 Nxa8 15. Qf3 { This sharp position occured in Bai,J - Wang,H Tianjin 2018Here I suggest the following interesting approach: } ( 15. Rxa7 $2 Qxd4 16. Rxa8 Bb7 { is very bad for White, who's king is too exposed. } ) 15... a5 $14 { Black sacrfiices a piece to fully consolidate and maintain his flexible pawn chain. } 16. Qxa8 Qd5 17. Qxd5 exd5 { There are no open files for White's rooks, while Black can easily advance his passers. } 18. Nb1 Nc6 19. Be3 Bh3 20. Rc1 g5 $1 { Black is ready to open the second front with ...f7-f6. The bishop pair and strong passers provide him full compensation for an exchange. } ) ( 9. Qc2 Bb7 { is covered in another Chapter. } ) ( 9. Ne5 { looks tempting, but turns ineffective because the e5-knight can be either chased or exchanged. } 9... Nd5 10. e4 ( 10. Ne4 f6 11. Nf3 a5 12. Bd2 Na6 $15 { was better for Black in Papaioannou,I - Malikentzos,S Achaia 2013 } ) 10... Ne7 11. Ndf3 { This was Chigaev,M - Sarana,A Chess.com INT 2022 In my opinion, Black could have claimed superiority by means of } 11... Nd7 $14 12. Bf4 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bb7 $15 ) ( 9. b3 { was played few times by Fabiano Caruana. even so, Black's issues seems easily solvable by means of } 9... c3 10. Nb1 bxa4 $1 11. bxa4 Nbd7 { Black develops his knight and makes it easier to push ...c6-c5. } 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. Nxc3 c5 $11 { Kasyan,A - Enkalo,M ICCF email 2021 } ) 9... Ba6 $5 { A relatively rare move. Black accepts some damage of his pawn chain, but it allows him to develop the queenside pieces. } ( 9... Nd5 { is much more common and leads to a complex struggle after } 10. Nc2 Be7 11. e4 $44 ) 10. Nc2 ( { After } 10. axb5 Bxb5 { White has nothing better than } 11. Nc2 { with transposition. } ) 10... Be7 11. axb5 Bxb5 12. Nb1 { A decent manoevre, The knight will be perfectly placed on c3, although it looks a bit slow. } ( { The only reasonable alternative is } 12. Nf3 Nbd7 13. Bd2 a5 14. Na3 { White was trying to put pressure on Black's queenside pawns in Millstone,M - Dias,V ICCF email 2016 Among few interesting possibilities, I mostly like } 14... Bb4 $14 15. Nxb5 cxb5 { The rest few moves are forced: } 16. Ne5 Bxd2 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18. Qxd2 a4 { The queenside pawn majority provides Black excellent compensation for an exchange. } ) 12... Nbd7 13. Nc3 Nd5 { Black has to cover the long diagonal. } 14. e4 ( { In case of } 14. Nxb5 cxb5 15. e4 Nb4 16. Nxb4 Bxb4 17. e5 a5 $1 { Black takes over initiative. Of course, sacrificing an exchange is a usual measure in such positions. } ) 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nb6 16. h4 ( { After } 16. Qg4 Kh8 17. h4 a5 18. Na3 Na4 { Black manages to interrupt White's plans by attacking c3. } ) 16... a6 17. Qh5 ( { Hardly attractive is } 17. Bf4 Ba4 18. Qe2 a5 { The a-passer is a cause of worries for White. } ) 17... Qe8 { A decent defensive approach - the queen's opposition on the diagonal yields Black an important resourse with ...f7-f5. } 18. Re1 { We have been following the game Caruana,F - Robson,R Saint Louis 2023 In my opinion, Black could have opted for ambitious } 18... Na4 $14 19. Bd2 Nb2 20. Reb1 Nd3 $13 { With such a strong knight, Black feels free to challenge opponent's centre with ...c6-c5 or e6-e5. white may found himself overextended. } *
