1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O dxc4 8. Qc1 { This was played by few strong players, but there are no real merits, comparing to 8.Qc2 - White's setup is artificial. } ( 8. Bf4 $6 { A dubious move - the bishop is definitely misplaced and it allows Black to consolidate with .. .Nf6-d5. } 8... Nd5 9. Bg5 ( 9. Ne5 b5 $17 { Bullen,A - Jascenko,O Teplice 2015 } ) 9... f6 10. Bc1 b5 11. e4 Nb6 $15 { White lost many tempi, and his compensation is questionable. } ) ( 8. a4 { A radical way to prevent ...b7-b5. White also makes a3 vacant for his knight. On the flipside, it weakens b4 and makes it easier for Black to develop his queenside. } 8... Nc6 9. Bc3 { This position took place in Muthaiah,A - Aravindh,C Thrissur 2014Black should have solved issues with c8-bishop by means of } ( { The passive } 9. e3 { meets } 9... e5 $1 10. dxe5 Ng4 $15 { Namitbir,S - Salem,A Chess.com INT 2022 } ) 9... Qe7 $14 10. Nbd2 e5 11. dxe5 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nxe5 { Black has no problems, to say the least. } ) ( 8. Na3 { A committing move - White accepts the double pawns, although exchanging Black's dark-squared bishop is a definite achievemnt either. } 8... Bxa3 9. bxa3 Nc6 { Black develops his knight with a tempo. For some reason, 9...b5 is more common, although with 9...Nc6 Black scored 3 ot of 3! } 10. e3 ( { In case of } 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 { Black will next play ...e6-e5 and obtain a better position due to structural superiority. } ) 10... b5 $14 { This ambitious move is a novelty it practically leaves White no choice. } 11. Ne5 { The only adequate response - White is trying to take advantage of favorable opposition on the long diagonal. } 11... Nxe5 12. Bxa8 ( { After } 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Qg4 c5 14. e4 Ne7 $17 { Black's passers prevail. } ) 12... Nd3 { A strong d3-knight offers Black a long-term initiative as it paralyzes White's heavy pieces, very much as in famous Karpov - Kasparov 16th game of match! } 13. Bxa5 Nd5 { There is no way out for a8-bishop. } 14. a4 b4 15. Qc2 Ba6 16. Bc6 Qg5 $36 { Both White's bishops are in danger, and his king is exposed either. } ) ( 8. Bxb4 { This exchange is basically unfavorable for White because Black grabs space and gets his queen's rook activated. } 8... axb4 9. Ne5 { The only way to justify it - now the d4-pawn is covered, and White is aiming to capture c4. } 9... Nc6 $1 { As in many lines of Catalan, the exchange of strong e5-knight makes it possible for Black to quickly moblize his queenside pieces. } 10. Nd2 ( { After } 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 Ra5 12. Bg2 Ba6 { Black is muc more active. Sachdev,T - Koneru,H Almaty 2022 } ) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 c3 12. bxc3 bxc3 13. exf6 cxd2 14. fxg7 Kxg7 { White had to struggle for equality in view of strong d2-pawn in Fernandez,F - Mareco,S Lima 2013 } ) ( 8. a3 { is actually one of White's most common options, but } 8... Be7 { was already covered with 7.a3. } ) 8... Bxd2 9. Nbxd2 ( 9. Qxd2 { transposes to 8.Qc2 } ) 9... b5 { As after 8.Qc2 Black doesnt concess his extra pawn. } 10. a4 c6 11. b3 ( { Hardly better is } 11. Ne5 Nd5 12. e4 Nb4 $15 ) 11... cxb3 12. Nxb3 Ba6 { This is the point - Black gains an important tempo due to attack on e2. } 13. axb5 Bxb5 14. Qc2 Nbd7 $15 { White is left with no sufficient compensation in Lalith,B - Nomin Erdene,D Budapest 2022 } *
