1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O dxc4 8. Nc3 { An ambitious continuation. White is ready to play a pawn down. His plan involves building a strong pawn centre with e2-e4, mostly after connecting rooks with Qd1-c2,Rad1, e.t.c. This position is similar to 5. Nc3, when a7-a5 and Bc1-d2 are included. } 8... Nbd7 { A flexible response. Black has 2 general ideas: connecting the pawns with ...b7-b5 and unlocking the c8-bishop with ...e6-e5. } ( 8... Nc6 9. a3 Bxc3 ( 9... Be7 10. e3 $44 ) 10. Bxc3 Nd5 { Bareev,E - Kramnik,V Monte Carlo 2005 } 11. Qa4 $14 Nb6 12. Qc2 $44 ) 9. Qc2 { The most consistent. } ( { Harmless is } 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qc2 $14 { Connecting the rooks and keeping an eye on c4 is the most reasonable approach. } ( 11. Rc1 { , as in Triapishko,A - Bluebaum,M Moscow 2018 is well met by } 11... Rb8 $14 12. Ne4 Qf5 13. Nh4 Qb5 { White still has to struggle for regaining the pawn. Black's chances seem preferable. } ) 11... c6 12. a3 Be7 { There is nothing wrong with f6-queen as it has f5 for a possible retreat. } 13. Rfd1 e5 14. d5 Nc5 $13 { The bishop pair provides Black decent counterplay. } ) ( 9. a3 Be7 10. e4 { was seen in Socko,B - Kucharski,T Jaroslawiec 1997 Here Black could have played } 10... b5 $14 11. e5 ( { After } 11. Nxb5 Nxe4 12. Ne5 Bb7 $15 { Black has the superior pawn structure. } ) 11... Nd5 12. Nxb5 Rb8 $13 { , obtaining excellent play on the queenside. } ) 9... c6 10. Rfd1 { A universal move in such positions. White streghtens d4 and makes Nf3-e5 more effective in the long run. } ( { Worse is } 10. a4 Qe7 11. Bg5 { Sumets,A - Wagner,D Haarlem 2014 in view of } 11... e5 $14 12. d5 h6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 $15 { Black's bishop pair seems to play an impotant role even if White will manage to grab the c4-pawn. } ) ( { The immediate } 10. e4 { can be well met by } 10... e5 $5 11. dxe5 Ng4 12. Bf4 Qe7 { Black will capture e5 and activate all his pieces. White has to struggle for equality. } ) 10... b5 11. a4 ( { Worth attention is } 11. b3 $5 cxb3 12. axb3 Bb7 { , but also then White's compensation will suffice only for equality, in best scenario. } ) 11... Qb6 12. e4 Be7 $1 { The b4-bishop did its job. Black retreats it to take control of g5. } 13. e5 $14 { The most ambitious choice. } ( { After } 13. axb5 cxb5 14. Bg5 h6 { Black was better in Sachdev,T - Bok,B Dubai 2017 } ) 13... Nd5 14. Bg5 Bb4 { White isn't allowed to play Nf3-g5, so Black has a solid position and ecent prospects on the queenside. } *
