1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O dxc4 8. e3 { This modest-looking move gained its popularity after Carlsen - Mamedyarov game, where White won in a great style. } 8... b5 { I find this move very logical, although the opposition on the h-a8 diagonal looks scary. } ( { The above-mentioned struggle saw } 8... Ra6 9. Qc2 b5 10. a4 c6 11. Nc3 Rb6 12. e4 { Carlsen,M - Mamedyarov,S Wijk aan Zee 2022 } ) 9. a4 ( 9. Ne5 { , as in Matlakov,M - Asadli,V Warsaw 2021 is well met by } 9... Nd5 $14 10. b3 ( { After } 10. a4 Bxd2 11. Nxd2 c6 12. Qc2 f6 13. Nef3 Na6 $15 { White has no adequate compensation. } ) 10... Ba6 $1 { The c4-passer is viable! } 11. a3 Bd6 12. bxc4 bxc4 $15 ) 9... Bb7 $1 { Black is ready to give his extra pawn back in order to develop the queenside pieces as soon as it possible. } ( { Weaker is } 9... bxa4 10. Ne5 Ra6 11. Rxa4 $14 { Maletin,P - Alexieva,S Benasque 2010 } ) 10. axb5 Nbd7 { Black's queenside pawns are vulnerable, but the pieces are able to cover them. } 11. Na3 { This is the most ambitious way of attacking c4 - White is aiming to activate his knight. } ( { The other natural continuations are: } 11. Nc3 Qe8 { A decent move. Black starts shooting b5. } 12. Qe2 ( { Tootless is } 12. Na2 Bd6 $11 { The a2-knight was awkward in Pashikian,A - Melkumyan,H Moscow 2008 } ) 12... Nb6 13. Rfc1 h6 $11 ) ( { I also examined other moves: } 11. Qe2 Bd5 12. Nc3 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 a4 $1 { A strong move. Black manages to consolidate the queenside. } 14. Nd2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nb6 $11 { The c4-pawn is intouchable. and Black is ready to collect b5. } ) ( 11. Qc2 Nb6 12. Rc1 Be4 13. Qd1 Qe8 $11 { Once again, Black has sufficient play against b5. } ) 11... Nb6 12. Qe2 { This position occured in Sapenov,D - Baranciuc,A Nakhchivan 2022 Here I suggest the following energetic way: } 12... Qd5 $14 13. Rfc1 ( { After } 13. Ne1 Ne4 { White faces serious problems with defending the d2-bishop. } ) 13... Ne4 14. Be1 Bxa3 { Black concesses his bishop to capture b5. } 15. bxa3 Qxb5 16. Ne5 Bd5 { White has definite compensation for the pawn, but it is sufficient for equality at the best. } *
