1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O dxc4 8. Bg5 { This is White's 2nd choice by statistics. White shows his intention to exchange on f6 in order to diminish Black's control of e4. On the other hand, yielding Black the bishop pair is a definite concession. } 8... Nbd7 { I like this flexible continuation. Black can choose a proper moment for ...h7-h6, and then it will possible to recapture with either queen or knight. } ( { The more common move is } 8... h6 { , and then } 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qc2 Nd7 { might lead to the same position. } ) 9. Qc2 ( { The rare } 9. a3 Be7 10. Nbd2 { was seen in Sargsyan,A - Deepan Chakkravarthy, J Chess.com INT 2021 Black had no reason for rejecting the most natural } 10... b5 $14 11. a4 c6 { , and then White has nothing better than } 12. axb5 cxb5 13. Ne5 Ra6 14. Nc6 { White grabs material, but loses his most active piece. } 14... Rxc6 15. Bxc6 Qb6 $15 { Blacks passers are very strong. White's material advantage has a symbolc value. } ) 9... h6 { The simplest. Black doesn't try to defend c4, but focuses on ...e6-e5 break. } 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qxc4 ( { Harmless is } 11. a3 Bd6 12. Nbd2 ( 12. Qxc4 e5 { transposes to 11.Qxc4. } ) 12... e5 { As usual, this break makes Black's play much easier. } 13. Qxc4 ( { After } 13. Nxc4 exd4 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Rfd1 c5 { Black had no problems in Spassov,L - Firman,N Albena 2014 } ) 13... Qe7 { Moving the queen in advance on view of coming...Ne4. } 14. Ne4 Nb6 { Black unblocks his bishop with a tempo. } 15. Qc3 exd4 16. Qxd4 Rd8 17. Nxd6 Rxd6 18. Qc5 Re6 $11 { Black has fully equalized in Churkin,M - Boger,R ICCF email 2017 } ) 11... e5 $1 { The most energetic - there is no need to waste a tempo for defending c7. } 12. Nc3 ( { In the event of } 12. Qxc7 exd4 13. Na3 Re8 { Black manages to regroup his pieces and put pressure on e2. } 14. Nc2 Bd6 15. Qc4 Ne5 16. Qxd4 Bf5 $44 { The bishop pair provides Black excelletn play for the pawn. Scharf,N - Hechl,G ICCF email 2015 } ) ( 12. a3 Bd6 13. Nc3 Nb6 14. Qd3 Bf5 15. e4 Be6 { Black had a comfortable play in Oganian,M - Khegay,D Sochi 2021 } ) 12... c6 13. a3 ( { After } 13. Ne4 Qf5 14. Nh4 Qh7 { the queen is placed somewhat awkwardly, but it isn't a big deal: } 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Qd4 Re8 17. a3 Bf8 $11 { White didn't achieve much in Kurth,W - Standke,W ICCF email 2010 } ) 13... Be7 { Black reasonably deviates from exchanging his strong bishop. } 14. d5 { The only attempt to fight for initiative. } 14... Nb6 15. Qb3 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Qxd5 Rd8 $1 { Black gives up the central pawn to activate his bishops. } 18. Qxe5 Qxe5 19. Nxe5 Bf6 20. Nd3 Bg4 { Activity of Black's pieces fully compensates for the pawn. Elwert,H - Van Oosterom,J ICCF email 2006 } *
