1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O dxc4 8. Qc2 { A top choice. White attack c4, vacates d1 for his rook and decalres his intend to play e2-e4. } 8... Bxd2 { A well-timed exchange. Black has to defend the c4-pawn, so ...b7-b5 should follow soon. } ( { The immediate } 8... b5 $6 9. a4 { isn't so good because } 9... Bxd2 ( { Or } 9... c6 10. axb5 $16 ) 10. Nfxd2 $16 { leaves the queenside pawns ruined. } ) 9. Nbxd2 { The most common and natural choice, although the d2-knight isn't as active as on c3. } ( 9. Qxd2 { also was tested on the gigh level, although it looks somewhat unnatural. } 9... b5 10. a4 ( 10. Ne5 Ra6 11. a4 c6 { leads to the same. } ) 10... c6 { Black is focused on maintaining his flexible pawn chain. } 11. Ne5 { The most consistent. White builds his initiative on the strong fianchettoed bishop. } ( { Dubious is } 11. Na3 $6 Qb6 12. Ne5 Bb7 $17 { Kunte,A - Swapnil,S Patna 2017 } ) 11... Nd5 12. axb5 ( { After } 12. Na3 f6 13. Nf3 Ba6 $15 { Black was able to consolidate and maitnain the extra pawn. Markoja,B - Sebenik,M Lichess. org INT 2020 } ) ( 12. Rd1 { was seen in Le,Q - Vidit,S Chess.com INT 2020 Here I suggest } 12... Ra7 $14 13. e4 Nb4 14. Nc3 Nd7 15. Nxd7 Bxd7 { White has some compensation for the pawn, but limited material baalnce favors Black. } ) 12... cxb5 13. Nc3 Qb6 $1 { A decent move. Black lets White to grab the pawn, but manages to quickly activate the queenside pieces and maintain the passers. } 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Bxd5 Ra7 { It is crucial to strengten f7, when White's minor pieces are so active. } 16. e4 a4 $13 { The king remains relatively safe, when Black has excellent prospects on the queenside. Maitre,F - Probola,R ICCF email 2019 } ) ( 9. Nfxd2 Qxd4 10. Rd1 { took place in Baryshpolets,A - Wang,K Kenner 2016 Here I suggest: } 10... Nc6 $14 11. Ne4 ( { After } 11. Nxc4 Qc5 12. Nbd2 Bd7 { White's compensation is questionable. } ) 11... Nb4 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Qxc4 c6 { Black's position is very solid. The issue of c8-bishop should be solved soon. } ) 9... b5 10. a4 { White puts pressure on Black's flexible pawn chain. } ( { The alternative plan is } 10. b3 cxb3 11. Nxb3 { White is bulding his compensation on the strong c5-knight. } ( { Less consistent is } 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Rfc1 c6 13. e4 { This position took place in Korley,K - Lee,M Charlotte 2022Now I suggest the following natural approach: } ( { The quieter } 13. e3 Nbd7 14. Ne1 { can be energetically met with } 14... e5 $5 15. Ndf3 e4 16. Ng5 c5 { Black gives the pawn back, but ovtain excellent play. Hilby,C - Hong,A Irving 2017 } ) 13... Na6 $14 14. e5 Nd7 15. Ne4 c5 $1 { A well-timed freeing break. } 16. dxc5 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Naxc5 { White has some compensation for the pawn, but Black's chances are by no means worse. } ) 11... Bb7 12. Nc5 ( { After } 12. Rfc1 Bd5 13. Nbd2 Na6 14. e4 Bb7 15. Qd3 b4 { Black had no problems in Georgiev,K - Bukavshin,I Legnica 2013 } ) 12... Bd5 13. e4 { A double-edged move. White builds a strong pawn centre, but weakens d4. } 13... Bc4 14. Rfd1 Nc6 15. a4 Nb4 { A perfect spot for the knight. Black gets stability on the queenside. } 16. Qd2 bxa4 17. Rxa4 Bb5 { Black was fine in Korley,K - Hong,A Charlotte 2021 } ) ( { Toothless is } 10. Ne5 Ra7 11. e3 Bb7 { Neutralizing the strong g2-bishop is Black's huge achievement. } 12. Bxb7 Rxb7 13. a4 { This position took place in Zimina,O - Kozak,A Katowice 2022 Here I suggest } 13... c5 $14 14. dxc5 Qd5 15. Ndf3 Qxc5 $11 { with a full equality. } ) 10... c6 11. b3 { White is aiming to unblock the c-file in order to secure c5 for his knight and put pressure on c6-pawn. } ( { Worse is } 11. e4 Nbd7 12. e5 Nd5 13. Ne4 { Sharnarthi,V - Liyanage,R Jamshedpur 2023 } 13... Nb4 $14 14. Qc3 Nb6 $15 { White's attacking prospects are questionable. } ) ( { Insufficient is also } 11. Ne5 Ra6 12. e3 Nd5 13. Ne4 f6 14. Nf3 { Sanchez Alvares,K - Osmanodja,F Chess.com INT 2020 } 14... Ra7 $14 15. Rfc1 Na6 $15 { Black manages to consolidate and maintain his extra pawn. } ) ( { and } 11. Rfd1 Na6 12. b3 Nb4 { Black gains an important tempo by attacking opponent's queen. } 13. Qb2 cxb3 14. Nxb3 Nbd5 15. Ne5 b4 $1 { Creating c3-outpost for d5-knight. } 16. Nxc6 Qb6 17. Rdc1 Bd7 18. Ne5 Rfc8 { The chances were mutual in Wurtinger,R - Andersen,J ICCF email 2012 } ) 11... cxb3 12. Nxb3 Ba6 { Since the long diagonal is blocked, Black reasonably places his bishop on f1-a6 diagonal. } ( { A common alternative is } 12... b4 $5 13. e4 Nbd7 14. Rfd1 { , when White prevents ...Nd5-c3 and maintains powerful pawn centre. Black is doing OK here but I still prefer text move. } ) 13. Rfd1 { White unpins the e2-pawn and places his rook in opposite to Black's queen. } ( { There are many alternatives at White's disposal: } 13. Nc5 b4 { This time White is unable to prevent ...Nf6-d5 with e2-e4. } 14. Rfd1 Nd5 15. Ne5 Nc3 16. Rd2 Qe7 { Black is getting closer for connecting his rooks. } 17. e3 f6 { White is asked to grab c6. } 18. Nxc6 Nxc6 19. Bxc6 Ra7 $15 { Black's chances are superior due to b4-passer. Mikhalevski,V - Dudin,G Saint Louis 2023 } ) ( 13. Ne5 { runs into } 13... bxa4 $1 14. Nc5 ( 14. Rxa4 Bb5 15. Ra3 a4 $15 ) 14... Qxd4 15. Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Bxc6 Ra7 17. Rxa4 Qd6 { , and White has to struggle for equality. } ) ( { Equally harmless is } 13. Rfc1 bxa4 14. Nc5 Bb5 15. Nxa4 { White grabs the pawn, but he is still a pawn down. } 15... Nbd7 16. Nc3 Nd5 $15 { Andreikin,D - Le,Q Chess. com INT 2022 } ) ( 13. axb5 $6 { assits Black im involving his queenside pieces: } 13... Bxb5 14. Rfd1 Nbd7 15. Ne5 a4 $15 { Yoo,C - Swiercz,D Saint Louis 2023 } ) 13... bxa4 { The easiest way of involving the a6-bishop. } ( { After } 13... b4 14. e4 $1 { Black isn't allowed to play ...Nd5-c3. In this case White maintains long-term compensation. } ) 14. Nc5 ( 14. Rxa4 $6 Bb5 15. Raa1 { is covered with 13.axb5?! } ) 14... Bb5 15. Ne5 { White reaches maximum activity for all his pieces. } 15... Ra7 { A decent consolidating move. Black moves the rooks away from dangerous opposition with g2-bishop. } 16. Nxa4 $14 { This most natural move is a novelty. } ( { The other possible continuations are: } 16. Ra3 { Anton,T - Padurariu,M Eforie Nord 2023 } 16... Qd6 $14 17. Nc4 Qe7 $15 { White has no proper compensation for 2 pawns. } ) ( { and } 16. e3 Qd6 17. Nc4 Qe7 $11 { with ...Nbd7 to follow. } ) 16... Nbd7 17. Bxc6 ( { After } 17. Nxc6 Rc7 18. Nxd8 Rxc2 { White had to struggle for eqiality in view of active c2-rook. } ) 17... Qc8 18. Rdc1 Rc7 $11 { White regained the pawns, but Black was able to reach a harmonious setup. } *
