1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Qc2 c5 8. dxc5 { This is White's second choice by statistics. White is trying to take advantage of opposition on the c-file, but Black isn't forced to immediately recapture on c5. } 8... d4 { An ambitious response. Black reasonably builds his counterplay on extension in the centre. } 9. Bxb4 { This exchange makes it eaiser for White to develop his queenside pieces, although it is still a certain concession. } ( { Undoubtedly, less promising is } 9. O-O Bxc5 10. Bg5 ( { Too slow is } 10. Ne5 Nbd7 11. Nd3 e5 $1 { For instance, } 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. b4 axb4 14. Bxb4 Qb6 { Black had a comfortable position in Nepomniachtchi,I - Riazantsev,A Moscow 2019 } ) 10... h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nbd2 e5 13. Ne1 { The knight is heading on d3. } ( { Ineffective is } 13. Ne4 Qe7 14. Nxc5 Qxc5 $15 ) 13... Na6 $1 { Black takes control of b4 and c5. } 14. Nd3 Qe7 15. a3 Bd6 { Black was fine in Nguyen,V - Milikow,E Budapest 2022 } ) 9... axb4 10. Ne5 { This move is the most challenging - White activates his fianchettoes bishop and prevents ...Nc6. } ( { The other natural possibility is } 10. Nbd2 Nc6 11. O-O e5 { As usual, Black starts extension in centre and activates the light squared bishop. } 12. Ng5 ( { Worse is } 12. Ne4 $6 Nd7 $1 13. e3 f5 14. Nd6 Nxc5 $15 ) 12... Qe7 $1 ( { Somewhat premature is } 12... h6 13. Nge4 Ne8 { The only way of covering d6. } 14. a3 $1 f5 15. Nd6 Nxd6 16. cxd6 Qxd6 17. c5 { White took the upper hand on the queenside in Buhmann,R - Fressinet,L Germany 2014 } ) 13. a3 { This change of pawn structure isn't optimal, but White needs to release pressure on a2. } ( { Dubious is } 13. Nde4 $6 { Ostmoe,G - Van Foreest,L Kragero 2022 } 13... Nd7 $1 14. Nxh7 Rd8 15. Nhg5 f5 { , and White suffers heavy material losses. } ) ( { and } 13. Nb3 $6 h6 14. Ne4 Bf5 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Be4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Qe6 18. Qd5 Qg6 $36 { Bocharov,D - Kosten,A Izmir 2004 } ) ( { Equal alternative is } 13. Nge4 Nd7 14. Nb3 Kh8 $1 { The last preparations before ...f7-f5. } 15. a3 { This position took place in Draeger,W - Fernandez,J ICCF email 2012 The most logical follow-up would be } 15... f5 $14 16. Nd6 Nxc5 17. Nxc8 Raxc8 $13 { Black's mobile pawn centre offers him decent counterchances. } ) ( { Somwwhat artificial } 13. Bd5 { was seen in Wei,Y - Dubov,D Dubai 2023 In my opinion, the most convincing way to meet it is } 13... b3 $14 { Black vacates b4 for his knight. } 14. Qxb3 ( { Dubious is } 14. Nxb3 $6 Nb4 15. Qd2 Nbxd5 16. cxd5 Nxd5 $36 ) 14... Nxd5 15. cxd5 Na5 16. Qd3 Qxg5 17. b4 { White regains the piece because the knight is trapped. } 17... b6 18. bxa5 bxc5 $13 { Black has excellent compensation for the pawn due to strong bishop and mobile pawn centre. } ) 13... bxa3 14. Rxa3 Rxa3 15. bxa3 Qxc5 16. Nde4 { A temporary activity. } 16... Nxe4 17. Qxe4 g6 18. Qh4 h5 $11 { Black can do with this weakening move. The chances were mutual in Van Wely,L - Gustafsson,J Soegel 2022 } ) ( 10. O-O Nc6 11. Rd1 { This makes a little sense as White cannot benefit from pinning the e5-pawn. } ( 11. Nbd2 { transposes to 10. Nbd2. } ) 11... e5 12. Nbd2 Qe7 13. Nb3 ( { Hardly better is } 13. Ne4 Nd7 14. Nd6 Nxc5 15. Nxc8 Raxc8 $15 ) 13... h6 14. Nfd2 Bg4 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 f5 { Black has decent attacking prospects, while White's extra pawn doesn't really tell. Schneider,I - Fridman, D Magdeburg 2021 } ) 10... Qc7 11. Nd3 Na6 { The most logical follow-up. } 12. O-O ( 12. Nd2 e5 13. Nb3 Bf5 14. O-O { transposes to text. } ) ( 12. Qd2 { , as in Polyik,P - Jamrich,G Budapest 2018 can be well met by } 12... Nxc5 $1 13. Qxb4 ( 13. Nxb4 $2 Nb3 $19 ) 13... Nxd3+ 14. exd3 Qe5+ 15. Kf1 Qf5 16. Qd2 e5 { Black's initiative in centre overwhelms White's extra pawn. } ) 12... e5 13. Nd2 { Preventing the nasty ...e5-e4. } ( 13. Qd2 { was tried in Kunin, V - Miton,K Havana 2015 Among Black's possibilities I prefer } 13... Bf5 $14 14. Nxb4 Nxc5 15. Na3 Nce4 16. Qe1 h5 $44 { Superior piece coordination and strong pawn centre offers Black plenty of play for the pawn. } ) 13... Bf5 14. Nb3 ( { Worse is } 14. Qb3 $6 { Bocharov,D - Bluebaum,M Chess.com INT 2022 } 14... Rfd8 $1 15. Nxb4 Nxc5 16. Qd1 e4 $15 { White is too crumped. } ) 14... Rfe8 $14 { This natural move is a novelty. Black overprotects e4 and makes the potential ... e5-e4 more effective. } ( { Less precise is } 14... Nd7 { Romanishin,O - Erigaisi,A Ciutadella de Menorca 2022 } 15. Qd2 Bxd3 16. exd3 Naxc5 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. Rae1 { In this complex position White's play seems easier because of strong g2-bishop. } ) ( { The same can be said about } 14... Rad8 15. Qd2 Be4 { Shevchenko, K - Wojtaszek, R Budapest 2023 } 16. f3 $1 Bxd3 17. exd3 Nxc5 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 19. a3 { White is ready to activate his fianchettoed bishop with f3-f4 at any moment. } ) 15. a3 ( { In the event of } 15. Qd2 Be4 $1 { Black manages to either exchange the bishops or provoke weakening ..f2-f3. } 16. f3 ( { Equally possible is } 16. Bxe4 Nxe4 17. Qc2 Qc6 $44 ) 16... Bxd3 17. exd3 Nxc5 { Black is now well-prepared for ..f3-f4. } 18. f4 e4 19. dxe4 Nfxe4 { Activity of pieces offers Black excellent play. } ) 15... bxa3 16. Rxa3 Nb4 { it is time to re-locate the knight. } 17. Qd2 Rxa3 18. bxa3 Nc6 { An optimal square for the knight - it covers both d4 and e5. } 19. Nb4 ( { After } 19. f4 e4 20. Nb4 Rd8 21. Nxc6 Qxc6 22. Nxd4 Qxc5 $11 { Black manages to regain the pawn in favorable situation, when the g2-bishop is locked. } ) 19... Na5 $1 { it is important to capture c5 in order to activate the queen. } 20. Nxa5 Qxa5 21. Bxb7 Qxc5 22. Rc1 Ne4 $44 { Black is ready to host his knight on c3. White's queenside pawns are vulnerable. } *

