1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Qc2 c5 8. cxd5 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qb6 10. e3 { This is the most logical - White is interested in maintaing blockade on d4. } 10... exd5 { Black accepts the isolated pawn, but it allows him to solve traditional issues with c8-bishop. } 11. O-O ( 11. a3 { was recently tried by few top players. } 11... Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 ( { After } 12. Qxd2 Ne4 13. Qc2 Nc6 { Black is very active, and White is unable to defend his blockading knight. } ) 12... Nc6 13. N2f3 ( 13. Qb3 { , as in Maghsoodloo,P - Esipenko,A Chess.com INT 2022 is well met by } 13... Qa6 { , preventing ..0-0. } 14. N2f3 Bg4 15. Bf1 { The only adequate response. Obviously, it shouldn't bother Black. } 15... Qa7 16. Be2 Bh3 $11 ) 13... Bg4 { The most active way of development. } 14. O-O Rac8 15. Qd3 { White manages to fix favorable pawn structure, but Black's pieces are currently very active. } 15... Ne4 16. Rab1 ( { Also after } 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. Nxb3 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Ne5 $11 { Black has sufficient play on the c-file. } ) 16... Rfe8 17. Rfc1 { The natural play by both sides led to this posiiton in Gelfand,B - Le,Q chess24.com INT 2022 Here my new natural idea is } 17... Nxd4 $14 18. Qxd4 Qe6 $1 { The active e4-knight puts pressure on opponent's kingside, so it makes sense to keep queens on the board. } 19. Rxc8 Rxc8 20. Ne5 Bf5 $11 { Black has nothing to worry about. } ) ( 11. Nc3 { has no independent value: } 11... Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. O-O { transposes to 11.0-0 } ) 11... Nc6 12. Nxc6 ( { Toothless is } 12. Bc3 Bxc3 13. Nxc3 Nxd4 14. exd4 Be6 $11 { Bai,A - Dardha,D Sitges 2022 } ) 12... bxc6 13. Nc3 ( { The rare alternative is } 13. Bc3 Ne4 $1 { Black temporarily sacrfices a pawn to exchange opponent's finachettoed bishop. } 14. Bxe4 ( { In case of } 14. a3 Bxc3 15. Nxc3 Nc5 { Black has sufficient play on the b-file. For instance, } 16. Na4 Nxa4 17. Qxa4 Be6 $11 ) 14... dxe4 15. Qxe4 Bh3 { Black gains a tempo and builds a checkmate net. } 16. Rc1 { This position occured in Morcin,T - Bruno,R LSS email 2020 Here Black should have continued: } 16... Rfd8 $14 17. Qf3 Be6 { Preventing ..g3-g4 } 18. a3 Bxc3 19. Nxc3 Qxb2 { Black has excellent play due to activity of all pieces. } ) ( 13. a3 { , as in Sviridova,V - Osmanodja,F Chess.com INT 2020 is well met by } 13... Bxd2 $14 14. Nxd2 Be6 15. Rfc1 Rfc8 16. Rab1 Rab8 $11 { Pressure on the b-file offers Black comfortable play. } ) 13... Be6 ( 13... h5 $5 { scores well for Black, although after } 14. a3 Be7 15. Na4 Qb5 16. Rfc1 { Black has a slightly inferior redaction, comparing to 13.Rc1 h5. } ) 14. Rfc1 { White assumes that the main struggle will be held on the queenside, so he leaves both his rooks there. } ( 14. Rac1 Rfc8 15. Rfd1 Bg4 16. Re1 { was seen in Osmak,I - Cyfka,K Legnica 2021 Here I suggest } 16... Bh5 $14 17. a3 Bf8 18. e4 Bg6 { with a sufficient counterplay against b2. } ) ( { After } 14. Na4 Qb5 15. Bxb4 axb4 16. Nc5 { White's knight reaches its destination, but it costs White weakening a2. } 16... Bf5 17. Qxf5 Qxc5 $11 { Black had no problems in Grischuk,A - Le,Q Chess. com INT 2022 } ) 14... c5 15. Na4 ( { After } 15. a3 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 d4 17. Be1 Rac8 $13 { Activity of pieces and strong d4-passer provides Black full compensation for White's bishop pair. Alvarez Villar,H - Rivas Maceda,J ICCF email 2018 } ) 15... Qa7 16. Bc3 ( { Bad is } 16. Bxb4 $2 axb4 17. Nxc5 Rfc8 { with a fatal pin. } ) 16... Bxc3 17. Qxc3 { White insists pressure on c5. } ( { Hardly more dangerous for Black } 17. Nxc3 Rac8 18. Ne2 { Turdyev,A - Brkic,A Mali Losinj 2021 } 18... d4 19. exd4 cxd4 20. Qd2 Rcd8 $13 { Black's pieces are active enough to support the passer. } ) 17... Rac8 { The c5-pawn is intouchable in view of ...Nf6-d7. } 18. Qa3 c4 { In general, provoking this move is a certain positional achivement for White. On the other hand, his knight is far away from d4. } 19. Rd1 Rb8 $14 { This innovation allows Black to develop counterplay on the b-file. } ( { Too slow is } 19... h5 20. Rd4 Rfd8 21. Rad1 $14 { Esipenko,A - Riazantsev,A Tallinn 2019 } ) 20. Rd4 Rb4 21. Nc3 Qb6 22. Rad1 h6 $11 { White struggles to make further progress because Black's pressure on b2. } *
