1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Qc2 c5 8. cxd5 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qb6 10. e3 exd5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Rc1 { The most common move by far. White is aiming for immediate pressure along the c-file in order to make Black's pieces tied with defending c6 and prevent c6-c5. } 13... Rb8 $1 { A tricky idea. Black undirectly covers c6 by attacking b2. Of course, avoiding dangerous opposition with opponent's fianchettoed bishop is a vital measure. } 14. Nc3 { White moves his knight towards c5. } ( { The other possibilities are: } 14. Bxb4 Qxb4 15. b3 h5 $1 { The advance of h-pawn is Black's key counter-attacking idea in many positions that emerge from 7.Qc2. } 16. Nd2 ( { The ''greedy'' } 16. Qxc6 $6 { cannot be recommended as after } 16... Bf5 17. Qa4 Rfc8 { White is forced to play the akward } 18. Na3 Rxc1+ 19. Rxc1 Qd2 $36 ) ( { The ''quiet'' } 16. Nc3 h4 17. Ne2 { is connected with a heavy positional idea: the knight's transfer on f4 might assist White in securing his king. } 17... Bd7 18. Nf4 hxg3 19. hxg3 { This position occured in Ding,L - Giri,A Ekaterinburg 2020 In my opinion, Black should have played } 19... Rfe8 $14 20. Qc5 ( { After } 20. Nd3 $6 Qg4 $36 { White's king gets in big danger. } ) 20... Ne4 21. Qxb4 axb4 22. Nd3 Rb6 $13 { The strong b4-pawn neutralizes White's slight structural superiority. } ) 16... Bd7 17. Nf3 Rfc8 18. Ne5 Qd6 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. h4 c5 21. Rd1 Qe6 22. Qd2 c4 $13 { 1-0 (70) Lazavik,D (2560) -Bluebaum,M (2670) Chess.com INT 2023 } ) ( 14. b3 Bd7 { Connecting the rooks and covering c6. } 15. Nc3 ( { In case of } 15. Bxb4 axb4 16. Nd2 Rfc8 $11 { The backward a2-pawn is equally weak as c6. Orian,N - Blagojevic,T Vrnjacka Banja 2023 } ) ( 15. Bc3 { was seen in Mareco,S - Haldorsen, B Abu Dhabi 2022 In my opinion, Black should eliminate the potential threat of ..Bxf6 by means of } 15... Qc5 $14 16. Qb2 ( { After } 16. Nd2 Rfc8 17. Nf3 { Black liquidates into a comfortable endgame. } 17... Qxc3 18. Qxc3 Bxc3 19. Rxc3 c5 $11 { Black has enough counterplay with ...a5-a4. } ) 16... Qe7 { White struggles to develop his knight in view of ..Ba3. } 17. a3 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Rfc8 19. Nd2 Qd8 { Black has no problems. } ) 15... Ba3 16. Rd1 Bg4 17. Rf1 { We have been following Cuenca Jimenez,J - Valenzuela Gomez,F Barcelona 2021 Here I mostly like } 17... Bh5 $14 18. Na4 Qa6 19. Bc3 Bg6 { Activity of pieces provides Black full compensation for his structural drawbacks. } ) ( 14. Qxc6 { is toothless: } 14... Qxc6 15. Rxc6 Bxd2 16. Nxd2 Rxb2 17. Nb3 a4 18. Nd4 Bd7 $11 { The active b2-rook fully compensates for isolated d5-pawn. } ) 14... h5 $1 { Black builds his counterplay on advancing the h-pawn, when the highlight is reaching the pawn on h3. } 15. a3 { This move invites simplifications. } ( { The potential danger behing h4-h3 push is well illustrated in the following case: } 15. Na4 Qd8 16. Bxb4 ( { After } 16. a3 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 h4 18. Qd4 h3 { Black was fine in Banikas,H - Ivic,V Terme Catez 2021 } ) 16... Rxb4 17. b3 h4 $1 { Black leaves the c6-pawn unprotected in order to take over the initiative. } 18. Qxc6 ( 18. a3 Rb8 { also scores well for Black - it provides him plenty of counterplay against b3. } ) 18... h3 $1 19. Bh1 d4 { White suffers from backrank issues, and activity of Black's pieces prevails. Vidit,S - Giri,A chess24.com INT 2020 } ) ( { The radical way to prevent h5-h4-h3 is } 15. h4 { , but it weakens g4: } 15... Ng4 $1 16. a3 Be7 17. Na4 { The only challenging try. White grabs a pawn. } 17... Qd8 18. Qxc6 Bd7 19. Qc2 { This position occured in Van Foreest,L - Petkov,M Terme Catez 2022 Black should have continued: } 19... Bxh4 $14 20. Nc5 ( 20. gxh4 $2 Qxh4 $19 { is crushing in view of 21...Qh2+, followed by 22...Bb5+. } ) 20... Bc8 $1 { A calm response. } 21. gxh4 Qxh4 { Black has a great attacking potential because his rook can be easilt joined the attack with ...Rb6-g6/f6. } 22. Bxa5 Qh2+ 23. Kf1 h4 { Black has sufficient counter-play, to say the least. White's position is hard to defend in a practical game. } ) ( 15. h3 { is another committing move. For instance, } 15... Re8 16. Na4 Qc7 17. b3 $6 { Dardha,D - Nihal,S Cappelle la Grande 2022 } ( { White soguld have played } 17. Bxb4 Rxb4 18. a3 Rb8 { with a balanced play - the pawns c6 and b2 are equally vulnerable. } ) 17... Bxd2 18. Qxd2 h4 { Black takes over initiative because } 19. g4 { runs into } 19... Bxg4 $1 20. hxg4 Nxg4 { with a stunning attack. } ) 15... Be7 { Black reasonably prefers to maintain his both bishops. } 16. Na4 Qc7 17. Qxc6 { The most forcing continuation. } ( 17. Bc3 { was seen in Blagojevic,D - Injac,T Niksic 2021 Here I suggest the consistent } 17... h4 $14 18. Bxf6 { Accepting the pawn is the most challenging reaction. } ( { After } 18. Bd4 h3 19. Bf3 Re8 20. Nc5 Nh7 $1 { Black has great counter-attacking prospects due to strong h3-pawn. } ) 18... Bxf6 19. Bxd5 Rd8 20. Bxc6 Be6 $11 { Black is active enough, so White has no real chances for converting his extra pawns. } ) ( 17. h4 Re8 18. Bc3 { , as in Makarian,R - Hovhannisyan,R Tornelo INT 2021 yields Black time for a successul regroup: } 18... Ng4 $14 19. Bd4 Bf6 { ,and then } 20. Bxd5 { runs into } 20... Nxe3 $1 21. fxe3 ( 21. Bxe3 Rxe3 22. Bxc6 Re7 { Black hs nothing to worry about. } ) 21... Bxd4 22. exd4 Re3 $1 { with a sufficient counterplay. } ) ( { The attempt to activate the fianchettoed bishop with } 17. Nc5 h4 18. e4 $6 { is dubious in view of } 18... h3 19. Bh1 Rb5 $15 { White's setup was dicey in Pavlov,M - Milikow,E Budapest 2022 } ) 17... Qxc6 18. Rxc6 Bd7 { Black wins the exchange, but White will get 2 pawns. } 19. Rc7 Bd8 20. Rxd7 Nxd7 21. Rd1 { This was played in major of games. White is aiming to capture d5 in favorable redaction. } ( { In case of } 21. Bxd5 { Black should play } 21... Bf6 $14 { The further liquidation of queenside pawns is unavoidable. } ( { Inferior is } 21... Nb6 22. Nxb6 Rxb6 { Chan,K - Kosakowski,J Prague 2023 } 23. b3 $14 Bf6 24. Ra2 $14 ) 22. Rd1 Bxb2 23. Nxb2 Rxb2 24. Bxa5 { In general, White should be happy with current material balance. However, activity of Black's rooks shouldn't be underestimated. } 24... Rc8 $1 { The most convincing. Black will get full control over 2nd rank. } 25. Bxf7+ Kxf7 26. Rxd7+ Ke6 27. Rd2 { Othwewise after 27...Rcc2 Black has nothing to worry about. } 27... Rxd2 28. Bxd2 Rc2 29. Bb4 g5 $11 { Although White has 3 pawns for an exchange, Black's position is safe because White fails to activate his king. } ) 21... Nb6 22. Nxb6 Rxb6 23. b4 ( { White achieves no advantage also after } 23. Bxa5 Rxb2 24. Bb4 Re8 25. Bxd5 Be7 26. Bc6 Rd8 $11 ) 23... axb4 24. Bxb4 Re8 25. Rxd5 Be7 { It is crucial to exchange one of powerful bishops. } 26. Re5 Kf8 $11 { Black had no problems in Nguyen,T - Le,Q Prague 2022 } *
