1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. a3 { An interesting alternative to the main lines with 7.Qc2 and 7.0-0. Black should make an important decision now. } 7... Be7 { This position is very similar to tabia with 5...Be7 - the only difference is including a-pawn moves. Basically, it should favor Black as it makes the consolidating b2-b3 very problematic for White. } ( 7... Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qc2 { was proved to be very comfortable for White - Black has scored only half a point out of 7 so far! } ) 8. O-O { A top choice. In such position White often fearlessly leaves his c4-pawn unprotected. } ( { The other possibilities are: } 8. Qc2 dxc4 9. Qxc4 b6 $1 { Fianchetto is definitely well-timed. Black will gain a tempo by attacking opponent's queen. } ( { Weaker is } 9... Nbd7 10. Nc3 $1 c5 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Ne5 { Black got under pressure along the long diagonal in Swiercz,D - Diermair,A Barcelona 2018 } ) 10. Nc3 ( { Equally harmless is } 10. Bf4 c5 11. O-O Ba6 12. Qc2 Nc6 $11 ) 10... Bb7 { Black takes control of e4. } 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Rfd1 c5 { This break comes on time - White's pieces are not active enough to take advantage of favorable opposition with Black's queen. } 13. Ne5 { The most active try. } ( { White achieves nothing special also with } 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Bf4 Qe8 15. Nd4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Rc8 $11 ) 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 cxd4 15. Nc6 { This move is forced. } ( 15. Qxd4 $2 Bc5 16. Qf4 { , as in Niemann,H - Dardha,D Almaty 2022 } 16... Nxe5 17. Qxe5 Ng4 $19 { loses to major material losses. } ) 15... Rc8 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Qxd4 Nc5 $11 { Black has a harmonious position. } ) ( 8. Nc3 { is an ambitious way of development, but it makes it difficult for White to keep control of c4-pawn. } 8... c6 9. c5 { Otherwise Black could grab the pawn and defend it with ...b7-b5. } 9... b6 10. b4 ( { After } 10. cxb6 Qxb6 11. Na4 Qb5 12. O-O Nbd7 { it is only a matter of time before Black will obtain a great position with ... c6-c5. } ) 10... Ne4 $1 { Activating the knight and vacating f6 for the bishop. } 11. O-O axb4 ( { Worse is } 11... Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Nd7 13. e4 $14 { Narvaez Parra,V - Jimenez Garcia,R Madrid 2018 } ) 12. axb4 Rxa1 13. Qxa1 bxc5 14. bxc5 Nxd2 { Black liquidates the strong bishop of opponent and diminishes White's control of e5. } 15. Nxd2 e5 16. dxe5 Nd7 $11 { Black regains the pawn and activates his bishops. } ) ( 8. Bf4 { took place in a few games. In my opinion, the easier way to reach equality is } 8... dxc4 $14 9. Qa4 c6 10. Qxc4 b5 { Black temporarily weakens c6, but fianchettoed bishop is aimed to support ...c6-c5. } 11. Qc2 Bb7 12. O-O Qb6 13. Nc3 Nbd7 $11 { Black's pieces are fully mobilized, and White cannot prevent the freeing c6-c5. } ) 8... dxc4 { I find this move very challenging for White: a3 isn't vacant for the knight, so he can only attack the c4-pawn with his queen. } ( { The solid } 8... c6 $5 { is a common alternative. } ) 9. Qa4 { White eliminates ...b7-b5 that means that c4-pawn will fall soon. } ( { The other options are: } 9. Qc2 { is somewhat played with same ideas, but it allows } 9... b5 10. Nc3 c6 11. Ne5 { This was Kudinov,A - Chigaev,M Ekaterinburg 2021 Black could have neutalized opponent's activity by means of } 11... Nd5 $14 12. e4 ( 12. Rad1 Bb7 13. e4 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 { is another possible moves order. } ) 12... Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Bb7 { Covering c6, so ...Nd7 is to follow. } 14. Rad1 Qc7 15. d5 cxd5 16. exd5 Ra6 $15 { Black's extra pawn prevails. } ) ( 9. Nc3 { White decalres his intend to occupy the centre, but it leaves Black with his extra pawn: } 9... c6 10. e4 b5 11. b3 cxb3 12. Qxb3 Ba6 13. Rfe1 Nbd7 $17 { Arnaudov,P - Kasimdzhanov,R Germany 2021 } ) ( 9. a4 { White vacates a3 for his knight, but this plan is too slow. } 9... c5 { Black starts shooting the centre. } 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Na3 ( { Worse is } 11. Qc2 $6 Nc6 12. Qxc4 b6 $15 { Ulaneo,R - Genta,A La Paloma 2014 } ) 11... Nbd7 12. Nxc4 b6 { Black manages to solve his only issue - the undeveloped c8-bishop. } 13. Nfe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Nd5 $11 ) 9... b6 { Fianchetto is well-timed: 10.Qxc4 will be met with 10...Ba6, winning a pawn. } 10. Ne5 { We have been following Daniels,J - Repka,C Seattle 2023Now I mostly like } ( 10. Nc3 Ba6 11. Rfd1 c6 12. Ne5 b5 13. Qc2 { took palce in Royal,S - Cheng,B Tegernsee 2022 Black should have continued: } 13... Qxd4 $14 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Bxc6 Rac8 16. Bxb5 Bb7 $36 { Desertion of light-squared bishop of kingside makes White's setup dicey. } ) ( 10. Qxc4 $6 Ba6 11. Qc2 Bxe2 { Doesnt provide White sufficient compensation for the pawn. } ) 10... Ra7 $14 11. Rd1 ( 11. Qxc4 { meets } 11... Ba6 12. Qa4 Bxe2 13. Re1 Ba6 { White's compensation for the pawn is questionable. } ) 11... Ba6 12. Bg5 { The most active move. White defends the central pawn. } 12... h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 { The c4-pawn is still intouchable in view of b6-b5. } 14. Nc3 Qe8 { Black is still up a pawn, and his chances are not worse, to say the least. } *
