1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Qc1 { A tricky idea that became very popular in the recent years. This modest move yields White some additional possibilities, comparing to 7.Qc2. } 7... Be7 { This time Black switches to usual Catalan paths, when his plans involves queenside development with c7-c6, b7-b6, and then Bc8-b7 or Bc8-a6. } ( { If Black responses in analogy to 7.Qc2 - } 7... c5 8. dxc5 d4 { , then } 9. Bxb4 axb4 10. Qf4 $1 { offers White some initiative,as was proved in a couple of games. } ) 8. O-O c6 { This allows Black to recapture ... cxd5 in case White captures d5. } 9. Bf4 { There is no better spot for White's dark-squared bishop. } ( { The alternatives are: } 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. b3 ( 10. Bf4 { transposes to 9.Bf4. } ) 10... b6 { Now both ...Bb7 and Ba6 look attractive for Black. } 11. Bc3 { This attempt to regroup the pieces by means of ..Bb2,Nbd2 was seen in Sargsyan,S - Bluebaum,M Warsaw 2021 Here I mostly like } 11... Ne4 $14 12. Bb2 f5 { Switching to Stonewall paths makes lots of sense because Black keeps control over e5. } 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qe8 { Black has a flexible setup. } ) ( 9. b3 { hardly significantly changes the route of play: } 9... b6 10. Bc3 ( 10. Rd1 Nbd7 { transposes to 9.Rd1. } ) 10... Bb7 { Black assumes, that e2-e4 will follow soon, so it makes sense to neutralize White's further pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal. } 11. Nbd2 Nbd7 12. Qc2 { This has to be played sooner or later - the c1-queen is mispalced, and e2-e4 break is White's only promising idea. } 12... Qc7 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 c5 $11 ) ( 9. Bg5 { is hardly promising for as White wouldn't benefit from capture on f6. } 9... Nbd7 10. Rd1 b6 { Black continues his central strategy - solving the issue of light-squared bishop. } ( 10... h6 $5 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 { is also worth attention. } ) 11. Ne5 { The only active try. } ( { Tootless is } 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nc3 Ba6 $11 { Muradli,M - Atakishiyev,E Abu Dhabi 2022 } ) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 { Black forces further favorable exchanges. } 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. cxd5 ( { Aslo after } 14. Qe3 Ba6 15. Nd2 Qc5 16. Qxc5 Nxc5 $11 { Black has nothing to worry about. } ) 14... cxd5 15. e4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Rb8 $11 { Activity of White's pieces is fully neutralized, and the e5-pawn feels vulnerable. } ) 9... Nbd7 { The most flexible continuation. Black chooses a proper moment for moving his b-pawn. } ( { The immediate } 9... b6 { is inaccurate in view of } 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Bc7 $1 { , claiming drawbacks of ...a7-a5. } ) 10. Rd1 { A standard Catalan move. White reasonably leaves thwe c-file unblocked for a while. This important position might be reached with different move orders. } ( 10. Qc2 { , as in Santos Latasa, J - Barski,R Caleta 2019 can be also met by } 10... b6 $14 11. cxd5 ( { After } 11. Nbd2 Ba6 12. e4 dxc4 13. Nxc4 c5 { Black manages to challenge opponent's centre just on time. A likely continuation is } 14. d5 exd5 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nfe5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Ra7 $1 { Black manages to consolidate and maintain the extra pawn. White still has some compensation, but it will not suffice for more than equality. } ) 11... cxd5 12. Bc7 { This move is still somewhat annoying, but now the b6-pawn is protected. } 12... Qe8 13. Rc1 Ba6 14. Qd1 Ra7 $1 { A decent idea - Black's effective regroup is aimed to neutralize White's pressure along the c-file. } 15. Nbd2 Qa8 { Finally the king's rook is unblocked. } 16. Rc2 Rc8 17. Rac1 Ne8 $11 { White has no advantage. } ) 10... h6 { A useful move. White is invited to show his cards. } ( { In the event of } 10... b6 11. Ne5 $1 Bb7 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nc6 { White manages to exchange one of Black's bishops. The middlegame that arises after both 13... Qe8 or 13...Bxc6 is solid, but rahter passive for Black. } ) 11. Nc3 ( { An equal alternative is } 11. Qc2 b6 12. Ne5 { The only attempt to fight for initiative. } 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. Nc3 { 1/2 (50) Semrl,M (2606) -Kunzelmann,F (2487) ICCF email 2017 } ( { In case of } 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. e4 { Black should keep the g2-bishop ineffective with } 15... d4 $1 16. Rxd4 Bc5 17. Rd1 g5 { , and then White has nothing better than } 18. Bc1 Ba6 19. Nc3 Rc8 { with transposition to 14.Nc3. } ) 14... Ba6 $14 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. e4 d4 17. Rxd4 Bc5 18. Rdd1 ( { The other retreat } 18. Rd2 { looks more logical, but after } 18... g5 19. Rad1 Bc8 $1 { it turns out, that White has nothing better than } 20. Be3 Bxe3 21. fxe3 Qc7 $15 { Black's structural superiority prevails because his knig is still safe. } ) 18... g5 19. Bc1 Rc8 $1 { Black has time to activate the rook because White cannot move his f-pawn yet. } ( { The immediate } 19... Qe7 20. Na4 $1 { lets White exchange Black's powerful bishop. } ) 20. Kh1 Qe7 { Connecting the rooks and unpinning the knight. } 21. f4 f6 22. exf6 Nxf6 $44 { Black's pieces are much better moblized, and it fully compensates for the pawn. } ) 11... Nh5 $14 { Depriving White's bishop of h2-b8 diagonal is among Black's key ideas in such positions. } ( { After } 11... dxc4 12. Nd2 g5 13. Be3 Nb6 14. Nf3 { White had promising play for the pawn in Gukesh,D - Saric,I Dusseldorf 2023 } ) 12. Bd2 ( 12. Be3 Nhf6 13. h3 b6 14. Ne5 Bb7 15. f4 Rc8 $11 ) 12... Nhf6 13. b3 { White covers c4 and shows his intention to push e2-e4. } ( 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. f4 b5 $1 { A little tactics that is based on vulnerablity of g1-a7 diagonal. Black manages to quickly activate his queenside pieces. } 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Be3 Rb8 18. Bf2 { This quiet move is aimed to unblock the e-pawn. } ( { The more aggressive way of handling the position is } 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Bxd5 a4 $1 { Black's pieces are somewhat crumped, and this move vacates a5 for the queen. } 20. Ba7 ( { Also after } 20. Bc6 Bb4 $1 21. Ba7 Qa5 22. Bxb8 Nxb8 { Black's chances are by no means worse. } ) 20... Rb6 21. Bxb6 Qxb6+ 22. Kg2 Nc5 $13 { This unabalanced position is full of dynamics. Black is doing well. } ) 18... Ba6 19. e4 { The consequences of this break are crucial for the whole line. } 19... b4 20. Na4 { The a4-knight is mispalced, but there was no adequate alternative. } 20... Rc8 21. Qb1 dxe4 22. Qxe4 Qe8 $11 { The chances are mutual. } ) 13... b6 14. e4 { This leads major simoplifications. } 14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Ne5 { a double attack. White regains a pawn. } 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qc7 { It is essential to avoid dangerous opposition on the d-file. } 18. Bxe4 Rd8 { An excellent preventive move. } ( { The careless } 18... Bb7 $2 { runs into } 19. Bxh6 $1 Qxe5 20. Qe3 $16 ) 19. Bc3 Bb7 $11 { Black will fully solve all the issues after ...c6-c5. } *
