{ [#] Another position out of a Catalan gambit line. As is often the case, defending the c4-pawn with ...b5 weakens the long diagonal. White just played Ne5 threatening the a8-rook. Black's task is to choose the best defense. } 9... c6 $1 { Black is happy to give up his pawn on c6 as taking it accelerates his development. } ( 9... Nd5 { offers White good compensation for the pawn after } 10. b3 $1 cxb3 ( { or } 10... c3 11. Nb1 $14 { when the c3-pawn will most likely fall. } ) 11. Qxb3 c6 12. Bb2 $14 { White has an advantage in space and development which more than outweighs the minus-pawn. } ) 10. Bxc6 { To give up the g2-bishop represents a big concession but White does not have promising alternatives. } ( { For some reason, the dubious } 10. a4 $6 { was played in the majority of games. } 10... Nd5 11. e4 ( 11. b3 $2 c3 $17 { doesn't work for White as Black can defend this mighty pawn with ...b4 if necessary. } ) 11... Nb4 12. d5 { This is the only reasonable try - White has to go all in! } 12... Qc7 13. Nxc6 N8xc6 14. dxc6 Ba6 $17 { White was positionally busted in Aditya,V - Kojima,S Budapest 2021. } ) ( 10. Nxc6 $6 Nxc6 11. Bxc6 Rb8 $17 { leaves White with a passive position, whereas Black's pawn majority on the queenside is quite strong. } ) ( { Compared to 9... Nd5 White has no time for } 10. b3 $2 { as } 10... Qxd4 $19 { is possible. } ) 10... Nxc6 11. Nxc6 Qc7 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 $15 { Black has the better game - White's king will feel unsafe with the g2-bishop missing. } *
