{ [#]White has some space advantage while Black has to find a way to activate his c8-bishop. On the downside, he has given up his dark-squared bishop. Black should try to free his game before White can take control. } 11... e5 $1 { The most energetic - there is no need to waste a tempo for defending c7! } ( { After } 11... c6 12. a3 Be7 { White can prevent ...e5 by } ( 12... Bd6 { steps into } 13. Nc3 $14 { with the idea Ne4. } ) 13. Qc3 $14 { when Black is still struggling to reach full equality due to his passive bishop on c8. } ) 12. Nc3 ( { In the event of } 12. Qxc7 exd4 13. Na3 Re8 { Black has enough counterplay, Scharf,N - Hechl,G ICCF email 2015. } ) 12... c6 13. a3 ( { After } 13. Ne4 Qf5 14. Nh4 Qh7 { the queen is placed somewhat awkwardly, but it isn't a big deal: } 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Qd4 Re8 17. a3 Bf8 $11 { Kurth,W - Standke,W ICCF email 2010. Black can play ...Bf5 or ...Ng6 next, exchanging or driving away the h4-knight after which the queen on h7 will re-enter the game. } ) 13... Be7 14. d5 { The only attempt to fight for the initiative. } 14... Nb6 15. Qb3 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Qxd5 Rd8 $1 { Black gives up the central pawn to activate his bishops. } 18. Qxe5 Qxe5 19. Nxe5 Bf6 20. Nd3 Bg4 { The activity of Black's pieces fully compensates for the pawn, Elwert,H - Van Oosterom,J ICCF email 2006. } *
