{ [#]A position from the line 5. Bd2 a5 6.Bg2 0-0 7.Qc2 c5 8.dxc5. Black is a pawn down for some positional compensation. How can he generate concrete counterplay? } 13... b3 $14 { Not the only move, but a strong one: Black vacates b4 for his knight. } ( 13... Kh8 $11 { Also a good move; Black unpins the f-pawn in preparation for 14... h6 15.Nge4 Nxe4 16.Nxe4 Bh3 17.Rfb1 f5. } ) ( { The immediate } 13... h6 $6 { doesn't work as well because after } 14. Nge4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bh3 16. Rfb1 Kh8 17. Nd6 f5 18. a3 $16 { White is too quick on the queenside. } ) ( { The "greedy" } 13... Qxc5 $2 { hands White a strong initiative after } 14. Nde4 $1 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 g6 16. Qh4 h5 17. Nxf7 $16 Rxf7 $2 { This leads to a decisive advantage for White. } ( 17... Kg7 $14 18. Ng5 $16 ) 18. Qf6 Qe7 19. Qxg6+ Kf8 20. f4 $1 { Very energetic - White wants to include his rooks into the attack. } 20... e4 21. Qh6+ Kg8 ( 21... Ke8 22. Bxc6+ $18 ) 22. f5 $18 { [%cal Yf5f6] } ) 14. Qxb3 ( { Dubious is } 14. Nxb3 $6 Nb4 15. Qd2 Nbxd5 16. cxd5 Nxd5 $36 { with more than enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 14... Nxd5 15. cxd5 Na5 16. Qd3 Qxg5 17. b4 { White regains the piece because the a5-knight is trapped. } 17... b6 18. bxa5 bxc5 $13 { Black has excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn due to his strong bishop and a mobile pawn center. } *
