{ [#]Let's have a look at a typical middlegame position arising from the variation 5.Bd2 a5 6.Bg2 0-0 7.Qc2 c5 8.cd5. White has the more compact pawn structure, while Black has free development and good prospects for his pieces. Black cannot advance his central pawn tandem and must find some other way to create counterplay. } 14... h5 $1 { This advance is characteristic for the line mentioned and this pawn structure in general. By moving the rook pawn forward Black provokes a weakening of White's kingside: If White stops it with h2-h4 then square g4 becomes weak, if he plays h2-h3 then Black can prepare a piece sacrifice by ... h4 with the idea to answer g4 with ...Bxg4. If White ignores the pawn it can march all the way to h3, creating tactical possibilities. Some variations to illustrate these points: } 15. a3 ( 15. h4 { White stops the pawn immediately but weakens g4. } 15... Ng4 $1 16. a3 Be7 17. Na4 { The only challenging try. White grabs a pawn. } 17... Qd8 18. Qxc6 Bd7 19. Qc2 { This position occurred in Van Foreest,L - Petkov,M Terme Catez 2022. Black should have continued: } 19... Bxh4 $14 20. Nc5 ( 20. gxh4 $2 Qxh4 $19 { is crushing in view of 21...Qh2+, followed by 22...Bb5+. } ) 20... Bc8 $1 { A calm response. } 21. gxh4 Qxh4 { Black has great attacking potential and his rook is about to join the attack via ...Rb6-g6/f6. } 22. Bxa5 Qh2+ 23. Kf1 h4 $44 { White's position is hard to defend in a practical game. } ) ( 15. h3 { Stopping the pawn in a different way has other drawbacks, e.g. } 15... Re8 16. Na4 Qc7 17. b3 $6 { Dardha,D - Nihal,S, Cappelle la Grande 2022. } 17... Bxd2 18. Qxd2 h4 $1 { Black takes over the initiative because } 19. g4 { runs into } 19... Bxg4 $1 20. hxg4 Nxg4 { with a crushing attack. } ) 15... Be7 16. Na4 Qc7 17. Bc3 { was seen in Blagojevic,D - Injac,T Niksic 2021. } ( { After the more forcing } 17. Qxc6 Qxc6 18. Rxc6 Bd7 $11 { Black wins the exchange, but White will get 2 pawns. } ) 17... h4 $14 18. Bd4 ( { White can force matters by } 18. Bxf6 { Accepting the pawn is the most challenging reaction. } 18... Bxf6 19. Bxd5 Rd8 20. Bxc6 Be6 $11 { Black is active enough, so White has no real chances of converting his extra pawns. } ) 18... h3 19. Bf3 Re8 20. Nc5 Nh7 $1 { Black has great counter-attacking prospects due to the strong pawn on h3. } *
